    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-02-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-02-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="341"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <head>341. National Security Study Memorandum 146<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d341fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 365, Subject Files, National Security Study
                        Memoranda (<gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>’s), Nos. 104–206. Top
                        Secret. Copies were sent to the Secretaries of Treasury, Defense, and
                        Commerce, and to the Director of Central Intelligence. In the absence of
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, who left Washington
                        that morning to accompany the President to China, <persName corresp="#p_HC1"
                            >Haig</persName> asked <persName>Kennedy</persName> to clear the
                        memorandum with the Department of State. (Memorandum from <persName
                            corresp="#p_HC1">Haig</persName> to <persName>Kennedy</persName>,
                        February 17; National Security Council, Secretariat Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 146) On February 18 <persName>Kennedy</persName> noted
                        that <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> had “no objection to the
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> as written” and that the
                        memorandum “should be issued with a date of February 17.” (Memorandum for
                        the Record by <persName>Kennedy</persName>, February 18; ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-02-17">February 17, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Policy Toward the <gloss target="#t_GDR1"
                            >GDR</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a study be prepared on <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >US</gloss> interests and policies with respect to the German Democratic
                    Republic.</p>
                <p>This study should examine the relevant issues in the context of: <list>
                        <label>(a)</label>
                        <item>Four Power responsibilities for Germany;</item>
                        <label>(b)</label>
                        <item>our position in Berlin;</item>
                        <label>(c)</label>
                        <item>our relations with the Federal Republic of Germany;</item>
                        <label>(d)</label>
                        <item>the development of the <gloss target="#t_FRG1">FRG</gloss>’s
                            relationship with the <gloss target="#t_GDR1">GDR</gloss>;</item>
                        <label>(e)</label>
                        <item>our relations with other East European countries;</item>
                        <label>(f)</label>
                        <item>the attitudes of our allies and third countries.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The study should consider <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> policy options over
                    the next few years, including timing of possible <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >US</gloss> actions. Each option should include a full discussion of
                    probable implications for <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> interests. Attention
                    should also be given to the implications of possible <gloss target="#t_GDR1"
                        >GDR</gloss> participation in international organizations and conferences
                    such as the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe (<gloss
                        target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>).</p>
                <p>The President has directed that the study should be undertaken by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for Europe and should
                    be completed by March 30, 1972, for consideration by the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Senior Review Group and, subsequently, by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
